# Laravel Project Guidelines
School Management system api (sms_api)

## Stack & Versions
- PHP 8.2
- Laravel 12
- Pest v3 / PHPUnit v11
- Laravel Sanctum (auth)
- Laravel Pint (code formatter)
- Laravel Sail (local dev)

---

## Architecture Rules
- Controllers must stay thin — delegate all business logic to Service classes
- All business logic lives in `app/Services/`
- All database access goes through Repository classes in `app/Repositories/`
- APIs must be versioned under `/api/v1`
- Use Form Requests for all validation
- Use API Resources for all responses
- Use Laravel Sanctum for authentication

---

## Laravel 12 Structure
- Middleware is NOT in `app/Http/Kernel.php` — configure in `bootstrap/app.php` via `Application::configure()->withMiddleware()`
- `bootstrap/app.php` handles middleware, exceptions, and routing registration
- `bootstrap/providers.php` contains application service providers
- `app/Console/Kernel.php` does not exist — use `bootstrap/app.php` or `routes/console.php`
- Console commands in `app/Console/Commands/` are auto-registered, no manual registration needed

---

## Models & Database
- Use `php artisan make:model --no-interaction` to create models
- Always create factories and seeders when creating new models
- Define casts in a `casts()` method on the model, not the `$casts` property
- When modifying a column in a migration, include ALL previously defined attributes or they will be dropped
- Eager load limits natively: `$query->latest()->limit(10)`

---

## APIs & Resources
- Always use Eloquent API Resources for API responses
- Always version API routes under `/api/v1`
- Use named routes and the `route()` function for URL generation

---

## PHP Conventions
- Always use curly braces for control structures, even single-line bodies
- Use PHP 8 constructor property promotion: `public function __construct(public MyService $service) {}`
- Use explicit return types and type hints on all methods: `function handle(User $user): bool`
- Use TitleCase for Enum keys: `FavoritePerson`, `Monthly`
- Use PHPDoc blocks over inline comments; inline comments only for exceptionally complex logic
- Use array shape type definitions in PHPDoc blocks

---

## Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive names: `isRegisteredForDiscounts`, not `discount()`
- Follow existing sibling file conventions for structure, naming, and approach
- Check for existing components/classes to reuse before creating new ones

---

## Testing (Pest)
- All tests use Pest v3: `php artisan make:test --pest {name}`
- Most tests should be feature tests; use `--unit` only for unit tests
- Run tests: `php artisan test --compact`
- Filter tests: `php artisan test --compact --filter=testName`
- Always use factories to create models in tests
- Check factory states before manually setting up model attributes
- Use `fake()->word()` / `fake()->randomDigit()` following existing conventions
- Do NOT delete tests without approval

---

## Code Formatting
- After modifying any PHP file, run: `vendor/bin/pint --dirty --format agent`
- Do NOT run `--test` flag, always run with `--format agent` to fix issues

---

## Artisan Usage
- Use `php artisan make:` commands to create all new files
- Always pass `--no-interaction` to Artisan commands
- Inspect routes: `php artisan route:list --path=api --except-vendor`
- Read config: `php artisan config:show app.name`
- Check env: read `.env` directly
- Use `php artisan list` to discover commands, `php artisan [command] --help` for options

---

## General Rules
- Stick to existing directory structure; don't create new base folders
- Do not change dependencies without approval
- Do not create documentation files unless explicitly requested
- Do not create verification/tinker scripts when tests already cover the functionality
- Be concise — focus on what matters, skip obvious details
- If a frontend change isn't reflected in the UI, the user may need to run `npm run build` or `composer run dev`
